Visuals for Association between Variables

Muhammad Hilmi Abdul Majid

Introduction

We will continue with exploring various ways we can display the data visually. In this topic, we will look at visuals that can be used for displaying relationship or association between variables. In this case, we may have two or more variables and we would like to know if there is any relationship between them, or if one affect the other.

We will be focusing more on the quantitative variables here, as the visuals that we have used in the previous topic apply to categorical variables. For example, if we have two categorical variables, let’s say gender and exam grade, we can draw a stacked, grouped, or segmented bar chart to visualize the relationship of the two variables.

We load the ggplot2 and dplyr packages as usual first. We will also be using the gapminder dataset from the gapminder package in some of the examples in this topic.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(gapminder)

Scatterplot

The easiest and most common method to display the association between two quantitative variables is the scatterplot. In a scatterplot, points are drawn onto the canvas where the x-y location of the point corresponds to the variables in the x and y-axes. It is used mainly to see the association of two quantitative variables.

To draw a scatterplot in ggplot2, we simply use geom_point().

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder, mapping=aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot
  geom_point()

We can see from the plot that there might be some association between life expectancy and GDP per capita. However, the relationship can be difficult to see because the points are clustered to the left of the plot.

To overcome this, let’s use a log transformation on the GDP per capita. There are two ways to do this. The first is to create a new column for the log of GDP per capita and call it lnGDP in a new data frame gapminder2.

# Modify the origingal dataset by adding a column called logGDP
gapminder2 <- mutate(gapminder, logGDP = log10(gdpPercap))

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot
  geom_point()

The alternative is to use scale_x_log10(). This produces the same result but with different scale labeling on the x-axis. However, using scale_x_log10() may cause confusion when reading the plot due to the uneven x-axis tick mark values.

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder, mapping=aes(x=gdpPercap, y=lifeExp)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot
  geom_point() +
  
  # Change the x-axis scale to log10
  scale_x_log10()

We can see more clearly now that the higher log of GDP per capita is, the higher life expectancy is. These two variables have a positive and almost linear relationship.

The geom_point() has several options that can be used to modify the visual’s properties including:

  • color: Color of the points

  • size: Size of the points

  • shape: Shape of the points. This is similar to pch option in the base plot(). Refer to the previous topic on the visualization with base R to see the point shapes.

  • alpha: Transparency of the points.

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot with the given options
  geom_point(color="steelblue",
             shape=1,
             size=1.5) +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

Adding lines to represent the relationship

We can add lines on the scatterplot to represent the relationship between the two variables using geom_smooth(). When using geom_smooth(), we can specify the method that we want to use for the line. If we want to draw a best straight line, we can specify method="lm" in the geom_smooth(). Note that “lm” stands for linear model.

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot with the given options
  geom_point(color="steelblue",
             shape=1,
             size=1.5) +
  
  # Draw a line using linear model
  geom_smooth(method="lm") +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

If the method is not specified when calling geom_smooth(), the smoothing technique will be used instead.

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="steelblue",
             shape=1,
             size=1.5) +
  
  # Draw a smooth line using LOESS
  geom_smooth() +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

The blue line drawn using geom_smooth() is the expected y-value at the specified x-value, whereas the grey area between the blue line is the 95% confidence interval.

Here are some options you can use for geom_smooth():

  • method: Specify the method to form the line. If it is not specified, a smoothed nonparametric method is used.

  • formula: May be used together with method to specify the formula used by the method.

  • color: Color of the line.

  • se: If TRUE, then the confidence interval will be shown. If FALSE, then it will not draw the confidence interval. The default value is TRUE.

  • level: The level of the confidence interval. Default to 0.95.

In the code below, we use method="lm" for linear model and set formula=y~poly(x,3) to specify that we are using the polynomial model with order 3. In this case, we try to form the line \(y=\beta_0+\beta_1x+\beta_2x^2+\beta_3x^3\).

# Specify the data and mapping
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="steelblue",
             shape=1,
             size=1.5) +
  
  # Draw a line using polynomial model of order 3
  geom_smooth(method="lm",
              formula=y~poly(x,3),
              color="tomato",
              se=TRUE,
              level=0.99) +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

Bubble Chart

Bubble chart is an extension of the scatterplot, where the size of the points corresponds to a third quantitative variable. To create a bubble chart, simply use size option in the aes() mapping whether global or local.

# Specify the data and mapping, change size according to pop
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp,
                                    size=pop)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot
  geom_point() +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

The plot above can be difficult to see. Let’s change the color, fill, and transparency using the color, fill, and alpha arguments in geom_point(). The shape=21 is a circle where we can modify its fill color.

# Specify the data and mapping, change size according to pop
ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp,
                                    size=pop)) +
  
  # Draw scatterplot using the given options
  geom_point(color="grey20",
             fill="cornflowerblue",
             alpha=0.5,
             shape=21) +
  
  # Change the axes labels, title, and subtitle
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder",
       size="Population size")

We see now that in general, countries with higher population size tend to have lower life expectancy and GDP per capita, but this is not always the case.

Marginal Plot

Marginal plot is another extension of scatterplot. In marginal plot, the marginal distribution or the distribution for each variable is added to the top and side of the plot in the form of histogram, boxplot, or kernel density plot.

To draw a marginal plot, we can use the ggExtra package and ggMarginal() function in it. First, let’s install and load the ggExtra package.

# Install the package, run once per R version
install.packages("ggExtra")

# Load the package, run once per R session
library(ggExtra)

The ggMarginal() function is used outside of the ggplot chain. We first save the scatterplot into an object, then use ggMarginal() and use the object as the argument.

# Save the ggplot object into a variable
plot <- ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="steelblue", shape=1) +
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder",
       size="Population size")

# Draw the marginal plot
ggMarginal(plot)

Here are some further customization that we can use for ggMarginal():

  • type: Change the type of marginal plot used. It can either be "density", "histogram", "boxplot", "violin", or "densigram" (a combination of histogram and kernel density). Default value is "density".

  • margins: Choose whether to draw the marginal plot for both x and y variables, or either of them only. Either "both", "x", or "y". Default value is "both".

  • size: Controls the relative size of the marginal plots compared to the scatterplot. The size is in ratio of the scatterplot. A size of 5 means the scatterplot is 5 times wider and 5 times taller.

The default, the kernel density is used for the marginal plot. But we can change this to other types by using the type argument and specifying it to .

# Save the ggplot object into a variable
plot <- ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(color="steelblue", shape=1) +
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder",
       size="Population size")

# Draw the marginal plot
ggMarginal(plot, type="boxplot", margins="y", size=10, fill='orange')

Additionally, if the ggplot object contains grouping using colors, we can maintain the grouping by setting groupColor=TRUE and groupFill=TRUE.

# Save the ggplot object into a variable
plot <- ggplot(data=gapminder2, mapping=aes(x=logGDP, y=lifeExp, color=continent)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x="Log of GDP per capita",
       y="Life Expectancy",
       title="Country's life expectancy by its GDP per capita",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder",
       size="Population size",
       color="Continent")

# Draw the marginal plot
ggMarginal(plot, type="density", groupColour=TRUE, groupFill=TRUE, size=10)

Scatterplot Matrix

If we have three or more quantitative variables we may want to draw scatterplots for each pair of variables. This can be done using scatterplot matrix. However, there is no easy way to draw the scatterplot matrix using only ggplot2 package. Thus, we can use GGally package and ggpairs() included in the package to draw the scatterplot matrix.

# Install the package, run once per R version
install.packages("GGally")

# Load the package, run once per R session
library(GGally)

To use ggpairs(), we need to specify the data from where the variables or columns are. Then, if we are not using all the columns, we can specify which columns we want to use for the scatterplot matrix using the columns argument

# Draw scatterplot matrix for the specified columns only
ggpairs(data=gapminder2, columns=c("logGDP", "pop", "lifeExp"))

Since the scatterplots involving the population variable (pop) is difficult to see due to its size, we can try using a log transformation for it.

# Add another column called logpop in the dataset
gapminder2 <- mutate(gapminder2, logpop=log10(pop))

# Draw scatterplot matrix for the specified columns only
ggpairs(data=gapminder2, columns=c("logGDP", "logpop", "lifeExp"),
        size=0.5) +
  
  # Add title and subtitle using labs()
  labs(title="Scatterplot matrix for GDP per capita, population, and life Expectancy",
       subtitle="Source: Gapminder")

There are a few things that the ggpairs() produces. First, it shows the kernel density estimate for each individual variables. Second, it draws the scatterplot matrix for each pair of variable. And third, it calculates the correlation for each pair of variables.

From the above plot, we can see that life expectancy has a positive relationship with the log of GDP per capita based on the scatterplot. That the correlation between life expectancy and log of GDP per capita is written as “0.808***”, showing that the correlation is statistically significant (i.e. significantly non-zero) after using the hypothesis test. On the other hand, the log of population exhibits weak association with life expectancy based on the scatterplot and correlation. We note however, that even though the correlation between the two is low (0.188), it is still significant due to the “***” shown. As for the log of GDP per capita and log of population, it seems that there is no relationship between the two and the correlation is low and not significantly different from zero.

Correlation Plot

Correlation plot or matrix is another alternative to scatterplot matrix, where we have three or more variables and we want to see the association between them. However, in the case of scatterplot matrix, the visual becomes cumbersome and overly complicated when we have a lot of variables. The correlation plot simplifies this by only showing the correlation between each pair in a matrix form and give colors correspond to the value of the correlation.

One way to draw the correlation plot is to use ggcorr() function included in GGally package that we have previously used.

# Draw correlation plot
ggcorr(mtcars)

Alternatively, we can use the ggcorrplot() function from the ggcorrplot package to draw a correlation plot. The ggcorrplot() requires us first to calculate the correlation matrix for the variables. We can use the cor() function in base R to do this.

# Install the package, run once per R version
install.packages("ggcorrplot")

# Load the package, run once per R session
library(ggcorrplot)

# Draw correlation plot
ggcorrplot(corr=cor(mtcars))

Here are some additional options that we can use for ggcorrplot():

  • hc.order: Set to be TRUE if we want to reorder the variables using hierarchical clustering. Default is FALSE.

  • type: Set to be "full" if we want both upper and lower of the matrix/triangle, "lower" if we only want the lower triangle, and "upper" if we want upper triangle. Default is "full".

  • lab: Set to be TRUE if we want to add labels that show correlation value for each pair. Default is FALSE.

# Draw correlation plot using the specified options
ggcorrplot(corr=cor(mtcars),
           hc.order=TRUE,
           type="lower",
           lab=TRUE) +
  
  # Add title using labs()
  labs(title="Correlation matrix for mtcars dataset")

From the plot, we can see that wt, hp, cyl and disp are positively related to each other. Similarly for vs, mpg, drat, am and gear. However, the two clusters seem to be negatively related.

Conclusion

In this topic, we have explored some visuals we can use to display association and relationship between variables. We mainly use different forms of scatterplot to perform this task as they are easy to be read and understood. But we can also use correlation values and matrix to further show the association between variables.
